ce:section.ce:para:
Finally, we have explored the photocatalytic performance of the CDs–CeO2 nanohybrids and compared their efficiencies with bare CeO2 and TiO2 P25 (a standard photocatalyst) via photodegradation of MO as a function of time under visible light irradiation at neutral pH (pH∼6). CeO2, TiO2 P25 and their nanocomposites with CDs displayed a time-dependent increase in degradation ability. The catalytic efficiency was found in the order: 0.1 wt % > 0.2 wt % > 0.3 wt % ∼0.05 wt % > 0.025 wt % ∼ CeO2 > TiO2 P25. From the above trend, we have observed that the photodegradation ability was increased with increasing the CDs amount in composites from 0.025 to 0.1 wt %, whereas higher amount of CDs reduced the photocatalytic activity due to the masking of CeO2 catalyst surface [43]. Besides, the poor photodegradation efficiency of TiO2 P25 towards methyl orange under visible light irradiation has already been reported by several other researchers [44, 45]. The highest photocatalytic activity of 0.1 wt % CDs–CeO2 nanohybrid is attributed to the increased visible light absorption ability and lowest band gap energy among all the tested photocatalysts. We propose that CDs act as photosensitizer due to their broad visible light absorption, and injects the photoexcited electrons to the conduction band (CB) of CeO2, thereby promote charge separation [13,14]. The charge separation between CDs and CeO2 is also evident from the fluorescence spectral analysis as there is strong fluorescence quenching of CDs following conjugation with CeO2. CeO2 itself has a weak response to visible light and promote electron transfer from valence band (VB) to CB [14,16–19]. This charge separation (electron-hole) process further triggers the formation of highly reactive superoxide (O2

                        .
                     ) and hydroxyl (HO
                        .
                     ) radicals via the reaction between photogenerated electrons and dissolved oxygen, and the reaction between holes and water molecules/hydroxyl ions respectively [14,16–19]. These highly reactive free radicals promote oxidative dye degradation. However, in our present study superoxide radicals (O2
                     −.) were found to play the most important role in the photocatalysis process within the pH range of 3–6.
